This is the summer website. Each lab is pretty thoroughly written (you can also look at su16 since the su17 ones aren't up yet). There is also assigned reading, although it is probably less helpful.

Perhaps you can email the head instructors and see if they can add you to the summer repo!

history.content:
Paul Hilfinger wrote some textbooks that he refers to when he teaches the class. They might be worth looking at. They are available online for free: https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs61b/fa16/materials/book1/java.pdf and https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs61b/fa16/materials/book2/data-structures.pdf 

Otherwise the comment below is probably your best bet.

Paul Hilfinger wrote some textbooks that he refers to when he teaches the class. They might be worth looking at. They are available online for free: https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs61b/fa16/materials/book1/java.pdf and https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs61b/fa16/materials/book2/data-structures.pdf

I am not able to take the class in the summer, but I would like to learn it in advance so I can be somewhat more ready when applying for internship in the Fall. I notice the past course websites have video lectures and reading lists.

I am not a fan of watching videos, so can I still have a very good understanding by only reading the listed chapters? For 61A, all I did was reading the notes by DeNero; I found it very useful yet precise, so I managed to get an A at the end. In addition, how can I practice problems on my own without the autograder?

Thank you in advance!
